# Make a timeseries plot
def make_plots( df , lo=-1 , hi=-1 ):
    df2= df
    df2.reset_index()
    if lo < 0: lo = 0
    if hi < 1: hi = len(df)
    for f in ['AMAG','XYANGLE']:
        fig, ax = plt.subplots( figsize=(16,4) )
        for subj in list(set(df2['SUBJECT'])):
            ax.plot( df2.loc[df2['SUBJECT']== subj,f ].index , df2.loc[df2['SUBJECT']== subj,f ] , 
                    linewidth=0.5 ,label= subj)
        plt.legend(bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 1), loc= 0, borderaxespad=0.)    
        ax.set_xlabel( 'IDX' )
        ax.set_ylabel( f )
    #del df2

In [118]:
# Function will train a given model for each feature in a list and then
# return an AUC ranking 
def get_ranked_features( df_train , df_test , est , flist ):
    res = []
    for f in flist:
        # Fit the model with given feature
        est.fit( df_train[[f]] , df_train['Walk'] )
        # Score the model on alternate dataset
        auc = roc_auc_score( df_test['Walk'] , [p[1] for p in est.predict_proba(df_test[[f]])] )
        res += [ (f, auc) ]
    return sorted( res , key=lambda x: x[1] , reverse=True )

Model Construction¶

Finally I'll try building some simple models. I will test the following: A very simplistic model where I pick features and apply cuts by hand Logistic regression with a few of the best features Gradient boosted tree with a few of the best features We can train on the left arm data and then test on the right arm data. It would also be fun to try training on LA+RA and testing on data from a different patient, or to train on LA and test on the full data RA data rather than just the cleaned data... but we'll get to that in a different notebook.

In [158]:
#
# First lets define some BOILER-PLATE functions for evaluating performance, etc..
#

# Function for training a model and grabbing the AUC
# given an input list of features
def get_auc( df_train , df_test , est , flist ):
    #print 'Fitting with len(flist) =', len(flist)
    est.fit( df_train[flist] , df_train['Walk'] )
    return roc_auc_score( df_test['Walk'] , [p[1] for p in est.predict_proba(df_test[flist])] )

# Make predictions with test data using a user-specified threshold
def predict_proba_above( est , df , thresh=0.5 ):
    return np.where( np.array([p[1] for p in est.predict_proba(df)]) > thresh , 1 , 0 )

# Iterate over range of thresholds to pick the optimal cut
def optimal_threshold( est , df ):
    best = (0.0,0.0)
    for thresh in np.arange(0.01,0.99,0.01):
        f1 = f1_score( df['Walk'] , predict_proba_above(est,df,thresh) )
        if f1 > best[1]:
            best = (thresh, f1)
    return best

# Dump a bunch of performance stats for the optimal threshold
def test_performance( est , df ):
    thresh = optimal_threshold( est , df )
    print 'Optimal threshold = %0.2f, corresponding F1-score = %0.2f' % (thresh[0],thresh[1])
    print classification_report( df['Walk'] , predict_proba_above(est,df,thresh[0]) )
    print 'AUC =', roc_auc_score( df['Walk'] , [p[1] for p in est.predict_proba(df)] )

# Function for getting the pionts in AUC curve
# I think there is one of these already in sklearn, but this is nicely catered
# to my input data format :-)
def get_auc_points( df , est ):
    X, Y = [], []
    df_sig = df[df['Walk']==1]
    df_bkg = df[df['Walk']==0]
    Lx, Ly = len(df_bkg), len(df_sig)
    for thresh in np.arange(0.0,1.01,0.02):
        y = sum( predict_proba_above( est , df_sig , thresh ) )
        x = sum( predict_proba_above( est , df_bkg , thresh ) )
        X += [ float(x) / Lx ]
        Y += [ float(y) / Ly ]
    return X, Y

Cut-based model:¶

In [243]:
# Transformer class will just reduce the dataset to the columns that we are using.
# This will come in handy for the other models as well.
class ColumnSelectTransformer(base.BaseEstimator, base.TransformerMixin):
    
    def __init__(self, col_names):
        self.col_names = col_names
    
    def fit(self, X, y=None):
        # This transformer doesn't need to learn anything about the data,
        # so it can just return self without any further processing
        return self
    
    def transform(self, X):
        # Return a DataFrame that just includes columns in
        # self.col_names
        return X[self.col_names]

    
# Estimator class will do the actual work and apply basic cuts.
# These are loosely based on previous studies, but mostly based on my feature ranking
# and comparing signal vs. background histograms by eye for each of key features.
class CutClassifier(base.BaseEstimator, base.ClassifierMixin):
    
    def __init__( self ):
        pass
    
    def fit( self , X , y ):
        # We don't need to do any actual work here since we are just applying hard cuts
        return self
    
    def predict(self, X):

        # The max acceleration should certainly be high, or at least should have a large
        # std deviation.
        res = np.where( (X['MAX_AMAG_155']>3.0)  , 1 , 0 )

        return res
    
est_cuts = Pipeline([
    ( 'ColumnSelectTransformer' , ColumnSelectTransformer(['MAX_AMAG_155']) ) ,
    ( 'CutClassifier' , CutClassifier() ) ,
])
